@page "/concepts/dto-pattern"

<DocPageMeta Title="The DTO pattern"
             Section="Concepts"
             Order="20"
             Status="DocPageStatus.Draft"
             Description="Why every Shift entity has two DTOs (ViewAndUpsert and List), how they differ, and when each one is used."
             Keywords="dto,viewdto,listdto,upsertdto,viewandupsertdto,shiftentityselectdto,hashid,projection" />

<DocSection Title="Two DTOs per entity">
    <p>
        Every entity in a Shift Framework project has exactly <b>two</b> DTOs.
        Not three, not one — two:
    </p>
    <ul>
        <li><code>FooDTO : ShiftEntityViewAndUpsertDTO</code> — used for reading a single record AND for inserting or updating it.</li>
        <li><code>FooListDTO : ShiftEntityListDTO</code> — used for list and grid projections.</li>
    </ul>

    <p>
        The two DTOs typically share most of their fields but differ in two
        important ways: how they shape foreign keys, and what the framework adds
        to each base class.
    </p>
</DocSection>

<DocSection Title="Why merge View and Upsert">
    <p>
        Most ASP.NET Core tutorials teach the &quot;CQRS triad&quot; — separate
        <code>CreateFooRequest</code>, <code>UpdateFooRequest</code>, and
        <code>FooResponse</code> classes. Shift Framework merges View and Upsert
        into a single class instead. The reason is empirical: in line-of-business
        admin apps, the same form is almost always used to <b>view</b> a record
        and to <b>edit</b> it. Same fields, same validation, same layout — only
        the mode (read-only vs editable) changes.
    </p>

    <p>
        Maintaining two near-identical DTOs that drift over time is more
        painful than maintaining one. The framework's <code>ShiftEntityForm</code>
        component takes a <code>T</code> generic parameter that's the same for
        both modes — you bind it to a single DTO class and the form switches
        between view and edit by parameter, not by changing types.
    </p>

    <DocCallout Type="DocCalloutType.Note">
        If you have an entity where create and update genuinely diverge — for
        example, a User entity where create takes an initial password and update
        never does — you typically handle it with a custom controller method that
        accepts a different shape, not by splitting the main DTO. The DTO stays
        merged for the 95% of cases where it's the same form.
    </DocCallout>
</DocSection>

<DocSection Title="What the base classes give you">
    <p>The two base DTO classes inherit from a common <code>ShiftEntityDTOBase</code>:</p>
    <DocCodeBlock Code="@(@"// Common base — every DTO has these
public abstract class ShiftEntityDTOBase
{
    public abstract string? ID { get; set; }
    public bool IsDeleted { get; set; }
}

// View+Upsert adds the four audit fields
public abstract class ShiftEntityViewAndUpsertDTO : ShiftEntityDTOBase
{
    public DateTimeOffset CreateDate { get; set; }
    public DateTimeOffset LastSaveDate { get; set; }
    public string? CreatedByUserID { get; set; }
    public string? LastSavedByUserID { get; set; }
}

// List adds a Revisions collection (audit history) but NO audit timestamps
public abstract class ShiftEntityListDTO : ShiftEntityDTOBase
{
    [JsonIgnore]
    public List<RevisionDTO> Revisions { get; set; } = new();
}")" />

    <p>
        Notice that <b>List DTOs don't carry audit timestamps</b>. Lists are
        typically dense grids where you wouldn't show <code>CreateDate</code> in
        every row anyway. The View DTO has them so the form can show "Created by
        John on March 12" in a side panel.
    </p>
</DocSection>

<DocSection Title="The IDs are strings, not longs">
    <p>
        On the database side, every entity has a <code>long ID</code>. On the
        wire, every DTO has a <code>string? ID</code>. The conversion happens in
        the framework's mapping layer, which encodes the <code>long</code> as an
        opaque hashid before serializing.
    </p>

    <p>
        The encoded string looks something like <code>"vBz0G2"</code> instead of
        <code>1234</code>. This serves two purposes:
    </p>
    <ol>
        <li><b>It prevents ID enumeration.</b> Without hashids, an admin URL like <code>/Product/1234</code> tells anyone who can see it that there are at least 1234 products and lets them probe <code>/Product/1235</code>, <code>/Product/1236</code>, and so on. Hashids make this attack class non-trivial.</li>
        <li><b>It keeps URLs and JSON consistent.</b> The same encoded string appears in URLs, in form bindings, and in JSON request/response bodies — there's never a place where the client has to know the underlying numeric ID.</li>
    </ol>

    <p>
        Each entity gets its own hashid alphabet (configured per-entity via attributes
        like <code>[BrandHashIdConverter]</code>) so a Brand ID and a Product ID
        with the same underlying number look completely different on the wire.
    </p>

    <DocCallout Type="DocCalloutType.Tip">
        You'll occasionally need the underlying <code>long</code> — for example,
        when querying related entities by foreign key in custom code. Use the
        framework's hashid helpers (<code>id.DecodeHashId&lt;Brand&gt;()</code> and
        the inverse) rather than reaching for the raw value directly.
    </DocCallout>
</DocSection>

<DocSection Title="The real difference between View and List: foreign keys">
    <p>
        The most non-obvious difference between the two DTOs is how they
        represent foreign keys. Here's a real example from a production codebase:
    </p>

    <DocCodeBlock Code="@(@"// View+Upsert — foreign key as a structured object
public class AutolineBrandMappingDTO : ShiftEntityViewAndUpsertDTO
{
    public override string? ID { get; set; }
    public string AutolineCode { get; set; } = default!;
    public string BrandAbbreviation { get; set; } = default!;

    [BrandHashIdConverter]
    public ShiftEntitySelectDTO Brand { get; set; } = default!;   // ← structured
}

// List — foreign key as a plain ID string
public class AutolineBrandMappingListDTO : ShiftEntityListDTO
{
    public override string? ID { get; set; }
    public string AutolineCode { get; set; } = default!;
    public string BrandAbbreviation { get; set; } = default!;

    [BrandHashIdConverter]
    public string? BrandID { get; set; } = default!;              // ← flat
}")" />

    <p>
        Why the asymmetry? The two DTOs are bound to two different UI patterns:
    </p>
    <ul>
        <li><b>Forms (View+Upsert)</b> need the related entity's display name to render an autocomplete picker. <code>ShiftEntitySelectDTO</code> carries both <code>Value</code> (the ID) and <code>Text</code> (the label) so the picker can show "Toyota" while binding the underlying brand ID.</li>
        <li><b>Grids (List)</b> need flat columns. The framework's grid component projects each row directly into table cells, and a nested object like <code>ShiftEntitySelectDTO</code> doesn't fit a column. A plain <code>BrandID</code> (or a <code>BrandName</code> string if you want the display name in the column) is what the grid wants.</li>
    </ul>
</DocSection>

<DocSection Title="When to use which DTO">
    <p>The framework picks for you in most cases:</p>
    <ul>
        <li><b>Single-record endpoints</b> (<code>GET /api/Foo/{id}</code>, <code>POST /api/Foo</code>, <code>PUT /api/Foo/{id}</code>) automatically use <code>FooDTO</code> as both the request and response shape.</li>
        <li><b>List endpoints</b> (<code>GET /api/Foo</code> with OData query options) automatically project to <code>FooListDTO</code> via the OData query pipeline. The mapper's <code>MapToList(IQueryable&lt;Foo&gt;)</code> method tells EF Core exactly which columns to <code>SELECT</code>, so list responses are efficient.</li>
        <li><b>Custom endpoints</b> (e.g. a "search" or "report" endpoint) typically still use one of the two existing DTOs rather than introducing a third shape, even if some fields go unused.</li>
    </ul>
</DocSection>

